. As the prevalence of kidney-related disorders rises due to factors such as diabetes and hypertension, the demand for apheresis treatments to support renal health is also expected to increase, providing substantial growth potential for the apheresis market in this application area.</p><p>Beyond the typical dialysis methods, apheresis has emerged as a valuable tool for treating certain conditions that complicate renal diseases, including autoimmune-related kidney disorders such as lupus nephritis. In these cases, apheresis removes harmful antibodies and immune complexes, which could otherwise exacerbate kidney damage. Furthermore, apheresis can serve as a bridge to kidney transplantation, helping patients manage their condition while awaiting a suitable donor organ. As advancements in technology improve the efficiency and accessibility of apheresis procedures, this market segment is set for continued growth, particularly with the aging global population and increasing rates of kidney-related diseases.</p><h3>Neurology</h3><p>In neurology, apheresis is increasingly applied in treating autoimmune diseases, particularly those that affect the central nervous system, such as multiple sclerosis (MS) and myasthenia gravis. Apheresis procedures like plasmapheresis are utilized to remove abnormal antibodies and immune complexes that contribute to the inflammatory process and neurological damage. This therapeutic approach helps reduce the severity of symptoms and can result in significant improvements in quality of life for patients suffering from debilitating neurological conditions. As the understanding of neurological autoimmune disorders grows, the role of apheresis in providing targeted treatment options is expected to expand, enhancing its presence in the neurology market.</p><p>The apheresis market in neurology is further strengthened by its ability to offer a less invasive alternative to conventional treatments such as immunosuppressive therapies, which may have signi